## Language and Dramatic Techniques in Presenting Conflict

Shakespeare’s use of language is pivotal in dramatizing conflict. The play employs:

- **Oxymorons and Antithesis:** Romeo’s use of contradictory terms such as "loving hate" and "brawling love" encapsulates the paradoxical nature of the conflicts he faces ([The Conflict in Romeo and Juliet, n.d.](https://www.ukessays.com/essays/english-literature/the-conflict-in-romeo-and-juliet-english-literature-essay.php)).
- **Derogatory and Violent Language:** Tybalt’s insults ("villain," "boy") and Lord Capulet’s harsh commands to Juliet ("green-sickness carrion") exemplify toxic masculinity and aggressive conflict ([The Theme of Conflict in Romeo and Juliet, n.d.](https://schoolworkhelper.net/the-theme-of-conflict-in-romeo-and-juliet/)).
- **Dramatic Irony:** The audience’s awareness of Romeo and Juliet’s secret marriage heightens tension, especially in confrontations involving Tybalt ([The Theme of Conflict in Romeo and Juliet, n.d.](https://schoolworkhelper.net/the-theme-of-conflict-in-romeo-and-juliet/)).

